# UDS Figma Write Safety

## Default posture

Figma reads are allowed for UDS work. Figma writes are denied unless the
user explicitly requested the write scope or a skill's instructions require
it after confirmation.

Do not mutate Figma while discovering, auditing, inspecting, or diffing.
Discovery agents are read-only.

## Page-target safety (preflight + postflight for every write)

`figma.currentPage` is NOT a safe write target. It persists from whatever
page the last read or inspection touched, so it can silently point at a
protected page (a `UDS Version: X.Y` page, a live component page, a
`_support` / `📗 Cover` / `🎬 Demo` / `🛝 Playground` page) while you
believe you're on the authorized draft. Creating nodes against
`figma.currentPage` — or `page.appendChild(node)` where
`page = figma.currentPage` — is how an in-scope task leaks an out-of-scope
write. (This rule exists because a stepper-draft task created a proposal
frame on the `UDS Version: 0.3` page: the build script used
`figma.currentPage`, which was still pointing at the version page from an
earlier version-detection read.)

Required BEFORE any node creation or mutation:

1. **Resolve the target page explicitly by name or ID — never read it from
   `figma.currentPage`.** Fetch the page node
   (`figma.root.children.find(p => p.name === '<exact name>')` or
   `getNodeByIdAsync('<pageId>')`), then either
   `await figma.setCurrentPageAsync(targetPage)` or append created nodes
   directly to that resolved page node — not to `figma.currentPage`.
2. **Assert the resolved page is in an allowed write scope before the first
   write.** If the page name doesn't match the authorized scope (e.g. it
   lacks `{Cursor}` for a scope #4 draft, or it's a `UDS Version: X.Y`
   page outside a release workflow), STOP — do not write.

Required AFTER any node creation:

3. **Validate placement at the page level, not just the node.**
   `node.screenshot()` and a node-scoped `get_screenshot` render the node
   regardless of which page it lives on — a clean node screenshot proves
   the node *renders*, NOT that it's on the right page. Confirm placement
   by reading the created node's page (walk `node.parent` to its `PAGE`, or
   screenshot the destination page) and checking it equals the authorized
   target.
4. **If a node landed on the wrong page, move it and report the slip.**
   `correctPage.appendChild(node)` relocates it (it does not duplicate).
   An unauthorized-page write is a scope breach in the write summary even
   after relocation — report it, never silently fix it.

## Allowed write scopes

The only routine Figma write scopes are:

1. **Release Notes frames**
   - Remove and rebuild only the frame named `Release Notes`
   - Target page must be the current `UDS Version: X.Y` page
   - Both UDS Tokens and UDS Components release-note frames must contain
     identical text if syncing release notes

2. **Component status page-name prefixes**
   - Allowed only when the user explicitly asks to sync status
   - Must report old page name and new page name
   - Do not infer status from spec completeness; status comes from Figma
     stoplight prefix or explicit user direction

3. **Cover-page version text**
   - Allowed only during a confirmed release workflow
   - Must report old text and new text

4. **Component drafts on a `{Cursor}{Ignore}` page in `UDS Components`**
   - Allowed only when the user explicitly invokes the
     `generate-uds-figma-component` factory skill (or equivalent
     prompt: "factory me an X", "generate a UDS component for Y") and
     names the target component title.
   - Target page MUST be a page in `UDS Components` whose name
     contains `{Cursor}` — typically `🟠 <Title> {Cursor}{Ignore}`
     (new or existing). The `{Ignore}` marker takes the page out of
     every UDS automation per `.cursor/rules/uds-figma-preflight.mdc`;
     the `{Cursor}` label marks it as Cursor's working draft.
   - **The `{Cursor}` tag is a standing write grant.** Any page whose
     name contains `{Cursor}` is Cursor's to create, modify, rebuild,
     or delete nodes on — freely, without per-action permission —
     until the user removes the `{Cursor}` tag. Removing `{Cursor}`
     (the designer's rename) revokes the grant; after that the page is
     designer-owned and writes need explicit per-target direction.
   - Writes outside that page (other component pages, the cover, the
     release-notes frame, `_support` / `📗 Cover` / `🎬 Demo` /
     `🛝 Playground` pages) are NOT covered by this scope and still
     require explicit per-target user direction.
   - Designer accepts a draft by RENAMING the page (drop
     `{Cursor}{Ignore}`, set the stoplight prefix). The factory must
     not auto-rename — that's the acceptance gesture.
   - If a `<Title> {Cursor}{Ignore}` page already exists for the same
     component, inspect it first to decide whether to resume/extend or
     rebuild — but because the `{Cursor}` tag is present, permission to
     rebuild is NOT required. The factory must still never auto-remove
     the `{Cursor}` / `{Ignore}` tags (that rename is the designer's
     acceptance gesture).

5. **Factory maintenance upgrades to a live component page**
   - Allowed only when the user explicitly directs a factory upgrade /
     maintenance run for a named live component (e.g. "upgrade
     metric-card to the current factory bar"), or confirms a specific
     change from a `figma-inventory` factory-version drift report. This
     is NOT a standing grant.
   - Target MUST be a LIVE component page in `UDS Components` — no
     `{Cursor}`, no `{Ignore}`. (Draft writes are scope #4 and are free;
     this scope is the gated, accepted-component path.)
   - **Per-change approval, never silent.** Every change is proposed and
     applied only on the user's explicit OK of that specific change —
     additive and breaking alike. Nothing auto-applies on a live page.
     The factory writes ONLY the approved scoped change, never a free
     rebuild.
   - A designer hand-edit (the live component differs from what the
     factory would produce) is surfaced, never overwritten.
   - A page tagged `{Frozen}` / `{NoFactory}` is excluded — reported as
     behind, never written (see `.cursor/rules/uds-figma-preflight.mdc`).
   - Every write emits the standard before/after/rollback summary.
   - Driven by the `generate-uds-figma-component` maintenance mode and
     `.cursor/rules/uds-factory-versioning.mdc`.

All other Figma writes require a direct user instruction that names the
target object or operation.

## Required before/after report

For every Figma write, return:

```markdown
## Figma write summary

- File: UDS Tokens | UDS Components
- File key: ...
- Page: ...
- Node/frame: ...
- Operation: create | update | delete | rename
- Old value: ...
- New value: ...
- Rollback note: ...
```

If a write fails halfway through, stop and report the exact last successful
operation. Do not continue with more writes until the user reviews the state.

## Destructive operations

Never auto-delete components, variables, component sets, pages, or library
assets in Figma.

The only allowed deletion-like routine operation is deleting the existing
`Release Notes` frame immediately before rebuilding it during release-note
sync.

